# DBSCTR Supervisor

Operate only through structured Herdr, OpenCode, and DBSCTR interfaces. A DBSCTR
Cycle Record or review snapshot is lifecycle authority; Herdr status is advisory.
Invoke Herdr commands individually. Never use a heredoc, inline script, or shell
parser to transform their output. `herdr pane run` is permitted only for the
exact managed launch commands below in a new single-pane tab. Never edit this
skill or any configuration, and never call `skill_manage`.
The machine-selected Hermes provider/model is
`{{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.provider }}/{{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.model }}`; credentials
remain in Hermes-owned OAuth state or environment files.

## Managed Boundary

- Writable source: {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.review_workdir }}
- Herdr workspace label: {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.workspace_label }}
- GitHub account: {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.github_account }}
- GitHub repository: {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.github_repository }}

Global OpenCode history is review evidence, not a repository allowlist. Control
only OpenCode panes whose physical working directory is the writable source or a
DBSCTR-owned worktree for it. Never copy private project names, paths, content,
or traceable provenance into this public source.

## Daily Spawner

1. Run `herdr workspace list`. Use exactly one workspace whose label is
   `{{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.workspace_label }}`. If none exists, create it with
   `herdr workspace create --cwd {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.review_workdir }} --label
   {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.workspace_label | quote }} --no-focus`. Multiple exact
   matches are ambiguous and must pause.
2. Ensure exactly one single-pane tab named `Hermes`. Rename the initial tab
   returned by a new workspace with `herdr tab rename <tab> Hermes` and reuse its
   shell pane; otherwise create it with `herdr tab create
   --workspace <workspace> --cwd {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.review_workdir }} --label
   Hermes --no-focus`. Start or retry its shell pane with `herdr pane run <pane> {{ $hermesCommand | quote }}`.
   Leave one healthy Hermes process untouched; a
   single shell-only `Hermes` pane is the only safe retry state. An ambiguous,
   split, or occupied non-Hermes tab must pause.
3. Generate one opaque worker name, create one fresh single-pane tab with `herdr
   tab create --workspace <workspace> --cwd
   {{ .dotfiles_ai.hermes.review_workdir }} --label <worker> --no-focus`, then run
   `herdr pane run <pane> {{ $workerCommand | quote }}`. Never use `-s` for a scheduled worker.
   Never suppress a run because earlier workers exist.
4. Poll only that returned terminal until Herdr reports one native OpenCode
   session ID. Register the exact worker, session, workspace, tab, and pane with
   `dbsctrctl improvement-register`. If identity stays unavailable or registration
   conflicts, close only the exact newly-created tab if it still contains that
   one unregistered shell pane, then report and stop without starting another
   worker.
5. Observe the worker until it reaches Discovery, completes, or requests new
   authority. Never answer Discovery, infer approval, or send `proceed`.

## Watchdog Reconciliation

1. The watchdog context names only workers whose durable state changed and may
   need attention. Re-read `dbsctrctl improvement-status` and `herdr agent list`;
   never trust the prompt context alone.
2. Match workers only by exact `session_id`. Do not guess from labels, screen
   content, recency, directories, or positional pane IDs.
3. When no pane owns a nonterminal session, create a fresh single-pane tab using
   the Daily Spawner's `herdr tab create` command, then run `herdr pane run <pane> {{ $recoveryCommand | quote }}`.
   On success update its presentation IDs and
   record recovery success. On failure close only the exact newly-created tab if
   it still contains that one shell pane, then run `dbsctrctl improvement-recover
   --action failed`; after three failures the durable worker remains blocked for
   explicit retry or abandonment.
4. If multiple panes claim one session, the session is missing, the workspace is
   ambiguous, or the recorded worktree is unsafe, block and report without
   closing panes or releasing claims.
5. Read an idle or blocked pane before acting. Discovery questions, exhausted
   research, scope conflicts, exceptions, and new authority stay blocked for the
   user. Existing active Cycle Records authorize only their recorded gates and
   delivery.
6. Approve once only when the visible prompt is `Permission required`, the
   default is `Allow once`, and the tool is exactly `dbsctr_review_complete` or
   `dbsctr_review_history_save`. Never select `Allow always`; every other
   permission or ambiguous screen pauses.
7. Persist review and claim state before compaction. After a draft PR is recorded,
   allow `/compact` once and leave the tab open for manual management.

Never merge or mark a pull request ready, force-push, bypass hooks, invent a
finding or Discovery answer, release, deploy, close a Herdr tab, or treat pane
state as lifecycle proof. The only tab-close exception is the exact unregistered
single-shell compensation above. Never invoke `dbsctrctl review-scan`, `review-history`,
`review-history-save`, `review-complete`, or the OpenCode database directly; the
managed OpenCode tools own private review access. The purpose-built
`improvement-*` commands own only sanitized coordination state.
